From cou.: 7 Microfluidic chips were fabricated in PDMS (polydimethylsiloxane, Sylgard 184, Dow Corning GmbH) following the methodology implemented by Shin et al.47 A positive SU8 350 ± 30 μm relief pattern of the designed geometry was obtained through soft lithography techniques. After silicon wafer polymerization, the devices were individualized from the PDMS molds and sterilized in wet and dry cycles of autoclaving. Surface plasma treatment was used to bond the PDMS with the glass-bottom of 35 mm petri dishes (Ibidi) followed by the addition of poly-D-lysine (PDL) to enhance the surface–matrix attachment.
From Soup: 7 Microfluidic chips were fabricated in PDMS (polydimethylsiloxane, Sylgard 184, Dow Corning GmbH) following the methodology implemented by Shin et al. 47 A positive SU8 350 ± 30 μm relief pattern of the designed geometry was obtained through soft lithography techniques. After silicon wafer polymerization, the devices were individualized from the PDMS molds and sterilized in wet and dry cycles of autoclaving. Surface plasma treatment was used to bond the PDMS with the glass-bottom of 35 mm petri dishes (Ibidi) followed by the addition of poly- D -lysine (PDL) to enhance the surface–matrix attachment.
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 Based on the main characteristics of the microfluidic devices designed by Farahat et al.,48 we have developed a new geometry that uses trapezoidal columns to support the hydrogel via surface tension (see Fig. 1). The chip consists of a central chamber divided into three channels. The central cavity lodges the cells seeded while two symmetric and adjacent channels allow hydrogel filling. Two extra lateral channels allow the introduction of cell culture medium and growth factors in order to create the chemical gradient. Fig. 1D illustrates the main chip dimensions. Fig. S1 (ESI†) shows a picture of the microdevice next to a coin to compare the scale.
From Soup: 8 Based on the main characteristics of the microfluidic devices designed by Farahat et al. , 48 we have developed a new geometry that uses trapezoidal columns to support the hydrogel via surface tension (see Fig. 1 ). The chip consists of a central chamber divided into three channels. The central cavity lodges the cells seeded while two symmetric and adjacent channels allow hydrogel filling. Two extra lateral channels allow the introduction of cell culture medium and growth factors in order to create the chemical gradient. Fig. 1D illustrates the main chip dimensions. Fig. S1 (ESI † ) shows a picture of the microdevice next to a coin to compare the scale.
