From cou.: 14 To characterize the transport of growth factors used as chemoattractants in our assays, diffusion experiments using 20 kDa fluorescently labelled dextran (FITC–dextran, Sigma Aldrich, Germany) were performed. This particle has been used due to the similarities with PDGF in terms of molecular weight as well as in other diffusivity constants.50 The solution was injected simultaneously in both reservoirs of the same channel, diffusing homogeneously along the hydrogels. PBS was used to refill the opposite reservoirs in order to equilibrate the system. A 2X CPI Plan APO objective was used to visualize the diffusion phenomenon under a Nikon D-Eclipse C1 Confocal Microscope, acquiring fluorescence images every 500 ms for a total of 3 hours. Furthermore, the diffusion profile was obtained for the rectangular area between two trapezoidal posts starting in the entrance of channel 1 up to the end of channel 2, following the nomenclature given in Fig. 1C (see the diffusion of this fluorescent molecule into the whole device in the ESI,† Video S1).
From Soup: 14 To characterize the transport of growth factors used as chemoattractants in our assays, diffusion experiments using 20 kDa fluorescently labelled dextran (FITC–dextran, Sigma Aldrich, Germany) were performed. This particle has been used due to the similarities with PDGF in terms of molecular weight as well as in other diffusivity constants. 50 The solution was injected simultaneously in both reservoirs of the same channel, diffusing homogeneously along the hydrogels. PBS was used to refill the opposite reservoirs in order to equilibrate the system. A 2X CPI Plan APO objective was used to visualize the diffusion phenomenon under a Nikon D-Eclipse C1 Confocal Microscope, acquiring fluorescence images every 500 ms for a total of 3 hours. Furthermore, the diffusion profile was obtained for the rectangular area between two trapezoidal posts starting in the entrance of channel 1 up to the end of channel 2, following the nomenclature given in Fig. 1C (see the diffusion of this fluorescent molecule into the whole device in the ESI, † Video S1).
